There are other biohazards associated with meat besides mad cow prions.
Some are from the animal itself, and others are outside contaminents.   They
get into and onto the meat during the animals life,  as well as during
slaughter, butchering, and processing.

The list  includes parasites and bacteria.  My guess would be that a
grilling process that sears the outside will likely kill common surface
organisms like salmonella.  But leaving the inside extremely rare may be
risky.
